<br>
 LET THE WARS BEGIN!<br>
<br>
First, let us look at the differant AoE's.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Rain Spells: </u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> Low agro, decent damage over an area over two or threes rounds. A wizard's Rain Spells have a tighter range than the druid's spells. This breaks mez and makes it impossible to mez for several rounds. Use with enchanter in group is if enchanter is OOM or tanks are refusing to assist.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u> DD AoE's: </u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> High Agro but this is where a wizard really shines. This one is the one I will talk most about. Three of these puppies and even trains are wiped to cinders. The radius of these spells are fairly small and with careful targeting can hit two or three mobs leaving several others untouched. Uses are as follows. Tanks not assisting. Heavy pop or train that is resisting enchanter's AoE mez and has to be brought down quickly. <br>
<br>
 The heavy agro caused by these spells means any unengaged MoBs will come for the Wizard. A wizard needs Shield Skin on (&quot;You magical skin absorbs the blow&quot;) and Root and Shadow Step up. Extra MoBs are then rooted. First the wizard targets an unengaged MoB to let loose the spell after rooting another one in place to start with. He let's loosse the AoE. The MoBs (only two or three only, hopefully) charge the Wizard. Wizard roots. If after two tries roots are continued to be interupted Wizard Shadow Steps and Roots. Wizard then moves away from Rooted MoB and engaged tanks and casters. Root and repeat until all extra Mobs are scattered around the combat area. Enchanter follows and single target Mezz's the rooted MoBs. Wizard hopefully takes no more than half his HP in damage. Wizard says nothing about &quot;heal me&quot; to the cleric. Wizard re-AoE's the MoBs in the tank area, killing two to four. Now the un-assisting tanks can see single targets and are more likely to assist. This works extreamly well at lower levels with tanks that are not used to working with Enchanters. Sometimes it is prudent to start this action with a Rain Spell. <br>
<br>
Some one else lets loose a Rain Spell. Mez is already broken. The good Wizard cuts loose with two Rain Spells and then the AoE DD. Result is the Enchanter gets pissed at the Wizard (when it was the Druid that started it) but she sits and meds as the MoBs turn to smoking heaps. This is undesirable but the Enchanter has to watch and see who began breaking the mezzes to begin with. All the good Wizard is doing is assessing the situation and draining his mana for the safety of the party. Here are some clues to help the Enchanter properly assess the situation. Is there a wide area Rain Spell initually dropping? If there is, look at the Druid. When the first Rain Spell is dropped, who does the extra MoBs agro to first? Since the good Wizard is doing a follow up Rain Spell, the initual damage is done and agro list put into place by the bad caster 80% of the time or better.<br>
<br>
The final use of an AoE DD is when the tanks are assisting properly and there are only two MoBs in the radius of the AoE (remember, this is a tight radius) or if the the tanks are not assisting and there is only one mezzed MoB in the AoE's radius. The good Wizard watches the engaged MoB's hit points and determains when it is down to the point where the AoE will finish off the engaged MoB(s). Now, the good Wizard targets a MoB or party member on the side of engagement away from mezzed MoBs that he wants to keep mezzed. He lets loose the DD AoE. Engaged MoB(s) fly away from the center of the AoE into lootable piles as the Mezzed MoB in activated. The activated MoB then has to be immeadiatly engaged by the tanks. Wizard needs to Root the agroed MoB, if needed, and step away. Remember, a good Wizard's job is to do as much heavy damage to a MoB as possible with out getting agroed too much. In heavy pop or fast pull situations, a Wizard's mana rarely allows more than one nuke per MoB. Using the AoE kill/activate adds 50-80% more damage delt out to the activated MoB than is otherwise possible. This makes Enchanters nervious, especially if an unwanted mezzed MoB is in the AoE's radius. In this case, the halfway good wizard roots the MoB and steps back, as he did above, spreading the mistargets out. The Enchanter remezz's as the Wizard apoligizes for misestimating the AoE's radius.<br>
<br>
<br>
As far as Necro AoE DoTs are concerned, the only reason they should ever be used with an enchanter in the group is for the same reason that the Wizard needs to cut loose with AoE's. I.e.: someone else in the party is already making the Enchanter's job impossable and it is a follow up to that situation or the Enchanter is OOM. Even here, if the Wizard is a good Wizard and knows how to spread out the MoB's, an AoE DoT should NOT be used as the Enchater will follow up with single target Mez's. The DoT'er needs to be extra careful to make sure he <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  only</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> targets the MoBs that the tanks are engaging with single target DoTs, under normal circumstances. <br>
<br>
AoE's do have a place in the game and they do have a place in a group with Enchanters. The good Wizard will use them sparingly and with extream caution. In a group where others are breaking Mez's, a good Wizard will use them much more often and with little to no delay to save the party's butts.<br>
<br>
I have been grouped with my RL GF's Enchanter alt since 4th level. I have had alot of practice sizing up situations and reacting accordingly. My timing is pretty darn good, too. <br>
<br>
If more Enchanters would watch more and not just jump all over Wizards everytime an AoE is released (even if the initual AoE was not the good Wizard's AoE, he still gets the blame), then maybe this anomosity between these two classes could end and both classes could shine.<br>
<br>
 LET THE WAR END!<br>
