<br>
Well, for starters I'm actually unsure as to who is this single minded game player. Noted that you, Krungle as your Wizard, have grouped with other Enchanters, it seems from what you have been saying, that you have spent most of the playing time with only one Enchanter (your g/f). Now I see many pros and cons to this. Firstly it's very easy to get into a routine playing this way. You both know how to  communicate (practically without saying anything) so it's much easier to change tactics or play in a different style. However, this obviously makes it harder for you to change game tactics when playing with other Enchanters.<br>
<br>
I actually like having variety when grouping. I'm all for trying out new tactics, and at your Wizard's level this is a good time to do this. Over time, though, everyone notices how their strengths and weaknesses become advantageous or not, so they progress into what is your idea of a singular game play style. Ultimately this is by far the best way to go when you get to the 50+ level of game play where people have absolute specific roles. Yes, at times we can change those styles, group tactics, etc, depending on the circumstance, and it works if the people involved are normal intelligent folks. I for one am forever swopping spells when the group changes etc. This is a great test of ability, which in turn keeps the enjoyment factor up.<br>
<br>
At mid levels I liked to group with other Enchanters to see how they worked: pick up tips, good training for raids and general higher lvl playing. However, some of them really irritated me as they just would not change their spells and therefore their tactics depending on the circumstance. It all depends on whether the group is working efficiently. Thinking honestly here, I do think it is wise to stick to what you know best, first off, then once each of the group members has come to understand how the others work, that's when you can start experimenting. Though it is utterly beneficial to the group that everyone knows the plan.<br>
<br>
I have no prejudices against any class, we <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> ALL</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> have our jobs to do in the group. Yes, there have been times when I have got etremely annoyed with member(s) of the group for one reason or another but those were really bad situations, beleive me! In general if something or someone breaks the mez then I usually know exactly what/who it was as I have to have my eye on everything that's going on, I wouldn't be doing my job properly otherwise. Even if I say &quot;Something is breaking the mez!&quot; etc. (&lt;-- which is a tiny hint to those concerned), it still means I have a fair idea of what is happening. If I think something untoward is going on then I keep close watch through a few pulls to see, then either adjust to this, or have a quiet word with those concerned depending on what the problem is. In most circumstances if a mez gets broken, I just try doing it again. These things happen, I expect it to happen. Many times I switch to AoEs as people have split targets or something like that. It's fun but it is much more efficient for the entire group if we spend most of the time doing our jobs properly.<br>
<br>
Are many of these debates actually about what is best for the whole group or just who can be the most MVP through how much damage, spell casting or general overpowering can be done by one single player? <br>
(I have witnessed many a devious (or utterly mindless) player who has deliberately done something to undervalue another in the group, with the sole intent to make themselves look better when they &quot;come to the rescue&quot;).<br>
<br>
Btw - Enchanters at your Wizard's level have AoE Mez (I recommend it to be used, very good AoE stun that!) <br>
<br>
