  <i> Brell Serilis Server</i></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#313532><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ukrungleeisenguss.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Krungle Eisenguss</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Adventurer of Underfoot</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/4/01 12:01:41 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://members.aol.com/krungle101/krunglepic.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: AoE's Druids, Wizards vs. Enchanters</span><hr size=1> First, Brinklith, I did not prove your point as at this level an Enchanter does not have AoE stuns. AoE mez, only if they have researched it, is an effective tool as Aelnelda had pointed out. However, if the MoB is dotted, even this fails, as was the case I sighted in High Hold Pass.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  &quot;- who regulates the AE stuns?&quot; </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The Enchanter, of course.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  &quot;- who snares what mob? More mobs to fight=more possible runners or gaters.&quot; </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> At 44 (my Main)I have been summoned before but I have never ran into a Gater. I am sure I will learn about those soon enough. Runners are always a possibility, but I have never seen a stunned MoB run before. I think you have a moot point here.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  &quot;- who taunts the mob that isn't stunned?&quot; </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> I would assume the same person that taunts MoBs that are not mezzed. That would be the Tank. Also, my Wizzy Roots alot.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  &quot;- even after /serverfilter, what happens to the players on lower-spec PCs at 56k when there's an AE fight going on? more lag and LDs.&quot; </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The /serverfilter has helped lag out alot during raids. Any good caster also has either hotkeys tied to their spells or is proficiant with using the &lt;alt&gt; button. My Bard uses Hot Keys; my Wizzy uses a combanation of HotKeys and &lt;alt&gt;; my Pally (that be me <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) uses &lt;alt&gt;. LD's happen and nothing will stop them. If LD's were a valid reason not to do something then there would never be a Planes Raid.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  &quot;- While the group is resting what happens if a wanderer comes by while you're all licking your wounds?&quot; </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> A great 20th Century Philosifer coined a term &quot;The Strawman Arguement.&quot; This is where a an arguement is formed, usually with the &quot;what if...&quot; statement to attempt to invalidate a good point. Your point is moot because such can happen at anytime with a group using any type of tactics. Such an occurance is handled as best as it can be. Your question, I believe, stems from the assumption that a group will be lower on health and mana after an AoE battle than they would be in a single kill/mez the rest situation. Such an assumption is not valid.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  &quot;you're the first wiz I've heard complain of running out of mana on single pulls: most have learnt to save their mana&quot; </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> At higher levels the mana available to spell usage ratio increases. Also, over 20, a Caster gains more mana with the increase of INT (or wisdom). As one gains levels, one should also gain INT gear, thereby increasing the mana pool further. Also, at lower levels, a caster is pretty much stuck with Breeze if they get anything at all. Most Nukers do not <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> complain</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> about going OOM because they know that between the time they set off their last nuke and the time the next one is called for, they can generally have the mana for it. Also, High Pass Orcs is not a &quot;single pull&quot; camp; It is generally a double or quad pop camp situation. Since this is where my Wizzy has spent all of his time post 16, it is the only place I can draw referance from.<br>
<br>
As far as single pulling is concerned, this is always the preferable option in any group anywhere. However, there are places where this is impossable (a really good Monk is not always available, for instance). Also, situations like breaking a camp also sometimes call for differant tactics than holding a camp once the spawn is broken and the pops are staggered.<br>
<br>
Aelnelda, I am glad you are observant. However, not everyone always is. This thread began because a person playing an alt sent me a tell when a Druid was breaking mezzes telling me to stop AoE use because <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> I</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> was breaking the mezzes. This person said his Main was an Enchanter and if anyone <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> ever</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> used an AoE in his group they would be booted. Although he finally stopped the tells, he refused to believe the facts of the situation and argued deligantly that it was I that was inituating the AoE's and that the Druid was blameless. I have seen simulair anti-AoE/Wizard biases before.<br>
<br>
 I have learned alot about both the Enchanter Class and the Wizard Class from this discussion. My point was, however, and still is that 1) There are proper uses for AoE's and 2) There are many Enchanters that refuse to recognise point #1.<br>
<br>
As far as getting into habits, this can be deadly and also can make an adventure not happen because a &quot;needed class&quot; is not available. I have been in groups that have had one or no tanks, but were heavy in Pet Classes. I have also been in groups entirely made up of tanks. One of the best groups I was ever in was in High Keep Warrior Room that was made up of entirely Paladins. Also, I have been known to effectively control the Sarnak Tower in OT that everyone says needs an Enchanter in the group with a Necro on Crowd Control. I find Necros very effecent at Crowd Control. Necros, BTW, can also be halfway good healers in a pinch.<br>
<br>
I guess my point here is that by falling into a single habit and not utilizing all that is available to one's class a person is missing out on alot of possibilities of overcoming situations in the most efficent manner possible. Also, they run the risk of failing to attain certain goals.<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#414141><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ubrinklith.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Brinklith</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>The Jester of Avalon</span><br>  Posts: 263<br> <font color=#CC9900>(4/4/01 2:57:35 pm)</font><br>    <BR><img src=http://www.aelf.net/pics/brink-now.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: AoE's Druids, Wizards vs. Enchanters</span><hr size=1> Krungle, maybe I didn't make myself clear enough - I was pushed for time when I wrote that!<br>
<br>
You proved my point by showing that: The chanter had the pull mezzed. The mez broke, and they DIDN'T aggro the breaker, they aggroed the chanter. The chanter died. Maybe you did ok clearing the remainder, but the situation was under control before that, and resorting to AE attacks didn't rez the chanter that bought it. Therefore the group DID lose potential exp because the mez was broken. The moral: don't AE when the person whose responsibility is Crowd Control is mezzing. You get off scott free, the chanter suffers.<br>
<br>
AE stuns: so the chanter calls out when the next stun is due? what if the next stunner is lagging (likely, see below), or is recovering from a spell cast? Or is getting beaten on so can't get a cast off? The whole pull wakes up and all hell breaks loose.<br>
<br>
Gating mobs are a very real problem in mid-40s+ areas, eg: Karnors. You see one warning that they are about to gate, and if they get the gate spell off, they will return to their spawn point and heal up before coming back. An aggro'ed mob on its way back will bring any of its friends around as well. If you miss the gate (eg: waiting for stun to recover, no-one bashing, etc.), it'll go. If you're on many at once, the chances of missing a single gater is greater, hence the chances of bringing unwelcome guests to the party.<br>
<br>
The chances of MISSING a single mob in a group with an AE stun is high.  If they're about to run, they could easily slip out unnoticed. Not a moot point.<br>
<br>
Taunting mobs: the tanks have problems taunting a single angry mob off a caster. Who taunts MULTIPLE angry mobs off casters?<br>
<br>
Lag: I wasn't talking about hotkeys: try Crowd Controlling when there is lag - you know when you have a double pull because you've died.  Never mind hotkeying: you have nothing to react to. I guess raid strategies changed to accommodate lag, and normal fights should do their best to minimise it as well. Multiple aggro mobs (and the accompanying hits, graphics and battle spam) increase lag, /serverfilter or not. Simply telling 56k-ers to switch off /auction and hits off is not the sign of a good strategy which accommodates lag.<br>
<br>
The &quot;what if&quot; scenario is no Strawman: You kill more mobs at once regularly, the whole group will be low mana far more often than with single pulls. This is fact. Wandering (or unwelcome guests) are more likely as well (see my arguments above re: missing potential runners). Fighting large numbers of mobs at once is going closer to a zero mana situation than chanter mezzing. This makes the group more likely to have members die, or force an evac (and if the wiz or druid are burning mana on AE nukes, who's evaccing?).<br>
<br>
I haven't heard wizards complaining of being oom AT ALL - never mind at higher levels. Once they learn that they can't chain cast (usually pre-level 10), they get used to casting when they are needed. As I say, you are the first wizard I have come across who complains of running out of mana with one-at-a-time fights.<br>
<br>
As far as the War Room and the Sarnak Tower are concerned: the tactics there are so different than those needed at high levels. It's like playing a different game. The specialisms of each class become so pronounced that pick-up groups of 5 tanks and a wizard just do NOT cut it. <p><b>Brinklith Rioghbhardan</b> - The Jester of Avalon<br>
